# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1876 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fifth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National League and the third at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings, as one of the founding members of the new National League, won the NL's initial championship during this season with a record of 52–14.
[src:1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] The **1877 Boston Red Caps season** was the seventh season of the franchise.
[src:1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] Arthur Soden became the new owner of the franchise, who won their first National League pennant.
[src:1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1878-boston-red-caps-season] The **1878 Boston Red Caps season** was the eighth season of the franchise.
[src:1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1878-boston-red-caps-season] The Red Caps won their second straight National League pennant.
[src:1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1879-providence-grays-season] The **1879 Providence Grays** won the National League title in only their second season in the league.
[src:1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1880-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1880 Chicago White Stockings season** was the ninth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the fifth in the National League and the third at Lakefront Park.
[src:1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1880-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 67–17.
[src:1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1881-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1881 Chicago White Stockings season** was the tenth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the sixth in the National League and the fourth at Lakefront Park.
[src:1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1881-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 56–28.
[src:1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1882-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1882 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 11th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the seventh in the National League and the fifth at Lakefront Park.
[src:1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1882-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 55–29, 3 games ahead of the second place Providence Grays.
[src:1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The **1925 Pittsburgh Pirates** finished first in the National League with a record of 95–58.
[src:1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season] They defeated the Washington Senators four games to three to win their second World Series championship.
[src:1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The Pirates had three future Hall of Famers in their starting lineup: Max Carey, Kiki Cuyler, and Pie Traynor.
[src:1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Pittsburgh defeated the Brooklyn Robins, 21–5, on June 20 and two days later won 24–6 against the St.
[src:1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Louis Cardinals, becoming the first team since 1901 to score 20 or more runs in consecutive games.
[src:1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season] This feat was later matched by the 1950 Boston Red Sox.
[src:1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season] October 10, 1925, at Griffith Stadium in Washington, D.C.
[src:1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season] October 11, 1925, at Griffith Stadium in Washington, D.C.
[src:1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season] October 12, 1925, at Griffith Stadium in Washington, D.C.
